    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-05-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-05-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="463"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d463">
                <head>463. Memorandum From Robert W. <persName corresp="#p_KRW2" type="from"
                        >Komer</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d463fn1"
                        >Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Name File, Komer Memos,
                        Vol. I. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-05-28">May 28, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Mac—</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>, there’s a big flap over proposed <hi
                        rend="italic">Tanzania-Zambia railroad</hi>, designed to give Zambia an
                    alternate outlet to sea for its copper if S. Rhodesia goes sour. The IB turned
                    down this $400 million boondoggle as economically infeasible and <gloss
                        target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> feels the same way.</p>
                <pb facs="0847" n="799" xml:id="pg_799"/>
                <p>But now <persName corresp="#p_KKD1">Kaunda</persName> of Zambia sent word to
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> and Williams at Addis
                    Conference that Chou En-lai (due in Tanzania 3 June) was going to offer to build
                    it. <persName corresp="#p_KKD1">Kaunda</persName> pled for a Western pre-emptive
                    offer, and all our Africanists sent in a fervent plea to keep Chicoms out of
                    heart of Africa.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BGW1"
                        >Ball</persName> thought this nonsense and signed [so did] LBJ on Tuesday.
                    But <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Averell</persName> and <gloss target="#t_AF1"
                        >AF</gloss> are unwilling to take “no” for an answer, and former is in
                    London trying to get <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> excited. So we’ll
                    probably have a second round on this one. I’m staying loose for now, but doubt
                    that one Chicom railroad means curtains for us in southern Africa.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d463fn2">A notation in <persName corresp="#p_BMG2"
                        >Bundy</persName>’s handwriting in the margin of the source text reads:
                        “OK—keep an eye on it.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">RWK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
